What Marx theorized as his ideal concept of communism was essentially that the workers of the world would all rise up in unison and overthrow nations , landlords , and capitalists

The communist ‘ system ’ they would create afterword would be a world devoid of nation - states and socioeconomic classes ; instead , the workers themselves ( who would be everyone ) would collectively own and manage productive means and would have free , egalitarian access to the resulting products without any need for any sort of formal , top - down governance
Obviously this ‘ true ’ communism was so incredibly ambitious that later communist ideologues , especially Vladimir Lenin , conceptualized the need for an intermediate stage

This involved a vanguard party of enlightened workers that would begin the revolution on a smaller scale ( Russia ) , implement an intermediate * socialist * state to lay the groundwork for communism by enforcing things like collective production and consumption , and then once this system was functioning well , the socialist state could be dissolved to achieve true communism
The USSR obviously was never able to overcome the need for a strong socialist state , which is why many people argue that it never achieved ` true ' communism

In my view , the relevant question is n't whether the USSR was a ` true ' communist society ( it was n't ) but whether ` true ' communism is something that is even possible or realistic to accomplish ( it probably is n't )
